            "id": "bca62ef0a3784022932e3",
            "questionText": "An air conditioning system uses a refrigerant that undergoes a cycle. During the cycle, the refrigerant absorbs Q_C = 10,000 J of heat from the room and releases Q_H = 12,000 J of heat to the outside. The inside temperature is $!$T_C = 20^{\\circ}C$!$ and the outside temperature is $!$T_H = 40^{\\circ}C$!$. The cycle operates at 30% of the maximum possible (Carnot) efficiency. Calculate the actual work done by the air conditioner in one cycle.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "2d23dbf5e3a54309bd20e",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the ideal efficiency for a refrigerator operating on a Carnot cycle. To proceed, please identify the correct formula that relates the cold temperature $!$T_C$!$ and the hot temperature $!$T_H$!$ for the ideal efficiency of a refrigerator.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "eb2ed1a7-e528-4b88-8bd6-db3a653c73cf"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta=\\frac{T_C}{T_H-T_C}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta=\\frac{T_H}{T_H-T_C}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta=\\frac{T_C}{T_C-T_H}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "932653d123664df39aa92",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now that you have the correct expression for the ideal efficiency, convert the given temperatures to Kelvin (using $!$T(K)=T(\\circ C)+273$!$) and compute the ideal efficiency value. Then, considering the cycle operates at 30% of the ideal performance, calculate the actual efficiency by multiplying the ideal efficiency by 0.30. Enter the numerical value you obtain for the actual efficiency.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "4.395"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "fd04f7d4-aca6-4fa8-a6af-850d9be1e084"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
