        {
            "id": "d79b359d819c4c68b4460",
            "questionText": "A car engine operates in a four-stroke cycle approximating a heat engine. In one cycle, the engine takes in Q_H = 2500 J of heat from the combustion of fuel and exhausts Q_C = 1800 J of heat. Assuming the engine as a closed system, and given that during the expansion stroke the pressure remains constant with P = 1.5 \\(\\times\\) 10^5 Pa while the volume increases by \\(\\Delta V = 0.5\\, m^3\\), determine how much of the total heat intake is converted into work.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "cadfd0cf53d24aef90653",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by determining the fundamental relation for a cyclic heat engine. In a full cycle, the change in internal energy is zero. Which formula correctly relates the net work output to the heat absorbed and rejected?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea914822-cf42-4557-b08f-5f35daecfc70",
                        "7a27d98a-ef95-4796-b6f6-284ca65857e7"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = Q_H - Q_C$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$W = P\\Delta V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q_H = Q_C + W$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = \\Delta U + W$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e97b6690e2be475f9177f",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have identified the relation, use it to calculate the net work output of the engine. Compute the value by subtracting the rejected heat from the absorbed heat.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "700"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ea914822-cf42-4557-b08f-5f35daecfc70"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "2576db4670474f509fbf3",
                    "stepText": "Next, let\u2019s identify how to determine the efficiency of the heat engine. Efficiency in this context is defined as the fraction of the total heat intake that gets converted to net work. Which formula represents this efficiency?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2627d205-8411-4005-b844-ebf08203f968"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{W_{net}}{Q_H}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{Q_C}{Q_H}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{W_{net}}{P\\Delta V}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\eta = \\frac{\\Delta U}{Q_H}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "58d8955e05ea430bacc12",
                    "stepText": "Now, use the efficiency formula you've identified. Calculate the efficiency by dividing the net work output by the total heat intake. What numerical value do you obtain?",
